				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Well, I cannot understand it.<br /><br />Collectors collect all kinds of NES games:<br /><br />Licensed western games have a Seal of Quality.<br />Famicom games don't have a Seal of Quality.<br />Unlicensed games don't have a Seal of Quality.<br />Homebrews don't have a Seal of Quality.<br /><br />So, the collection of an NES collector is a wild mix of different kinds of games in different boxes and cartridge shapes.<br /><br />But the one category <em>Reproductions of Famicom-only games that are put on an NES cartridge</em> suddenly need a fake Seal of Quality because &quot;it looks nice&quot; and because &quot;it's fun to pretend&quot;?<br /><br />What the fuck?<br /><br /><br />And about the tricking of people: Maybe NintendoAge didn't intend to fool people. But there are enough idiots on the internet who get their hands on these reproductions and who sell it as some rare prototype or small batch release of a legitimate game. (The same idiots who list a cart-only &quot;Super Mario Bros./Duck Hunt&quot; as &quot;ultra rare&quot;.)<br /><br />And clueless people might fall for it, just because NintendoAge wasn't honest and didn't put their logo on it, but created a counterfeit game with a fake Seal of Quality, fake company logos, fake copyright notes and a fake barcode.</div>

					
